net.proteusframework.ui.miwt

Class MIWTApplication

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.proteusframework.ui.miwt.MIWTApplication
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Comparable, EventListener, LocaleContextSource, NotificationListener
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    SearchUIApp, WorkspaceMIWTApplication

    public class MIWTApplication
extends Object
implements Comparable, NotificationListener, LocaleContextSource

    Class that all MIWT applications must extend.

    Most initialization work should be done in init(), not in the constructor because the PackageManager will construct the application in order to get information about such as the name, dependencies, etc.

    The destroy() method is called by the WindowManager to close the application. Use the WindowManager to destroy the application, do not call this method directly as the WindowManager internals will not be cleaned up properly by MIWTApplication.destroy().

    User interface should be created in the userStarted() method, in response to an ApplicationEventType.USER_START_REQUEST event or in response to a FeatureEventType.FEATURE_REQUESTED event. The default implementation calls userStarted() in response to the ApplicationEventType.USER_START_REQUEST event and featureRequested() in response to the FeatureEventType.FEATURE_REQUESTED event. In any other case the environment and application may not be completely initialized in order to create user interface components correctly.

    Cleanup should be done in destroy() for things done in both init() and userStarted(). One obvious cleanup item is to close all windows.

    Author:
    Pat B. Double (double@i2rd.com)

    • Constructor Detail

      • MIWTApplication

        public MIWTApplication(@Nullable
                       MIWTSession session)

        Construct a new instance of the application. Do not allocate resources such as database connections in this method, use the init(). The PackageManager class will instantiate application objects to get meta information from them. Locale resources however should be initialized because methods such as getApplicationName will be called for display to the user. This constructor always initializes appLocale so that it is available for use by the subclass.

        IMPORTANT: The session object is kept in a private field in this class and should be retrieved only by the getSession() method. Another copy should never be stored in a field. Do not use the session value in the constructor. Wait until init() is called.

        Parameters:
        session - The MIWTSession that created the application, may be null.

      • getProvidedFeatures

        @Nullable
public Set getProvidedFeatures()
        Returns a set of features this application can provide. The WindowManager may start this application in order to start another application that depends on one or more of these features. The fact that a feature is returned by this method does not indicate that the feature is available, only that this application may provide the feature. The application must make the feature available using the WindowManager.provideFeature() method. This implementation return null.
        Returns:
        A set of Feature objects, may be null

      • getRequiredFeatures

        @Nullable
public Set getRequiredFeatures()
        Returns a set of features this application depends on. The WindowManager will not allow this application to run unless all the features are provided. This method may return null if there are no requirements. This implementation return null.
        Returns:
        A set of Feature objects, may be null

      • notification

        public void notification(NotificationEvent event)
        This method is used by the MIWTSession to send notifications about changes in the system. Some examples include when an application is started or stopped, features are provided or revoked, etc. An application does not need to register to receive notifications. If this method is overriden and a particular event is not handled, the superclass implementation should be called to handle the event.
        Specified by:

        Parameters:
        event - The notification event.

      • preRenderProcess

        public void preRenderProcess(Request request,
                             Response response)
        Process the request before rendering. This method does nothing. It will be called after Component.preRenderProcess(Request, Response, RendererEditorState) . Method calls on components, creating or destroying components, or nearly everything else having to do with the component tree and related data models must be done by queuing an event using EventQueue.queue(EventQueueElement). Otherwise you may get unexpected results.

      • stateRequested

        protected void stateRequested(Map state)
        This method is called when the application is requested to change to a given state. The application can respond by providing the UI for the given state. Otherwise, the application may do nothing or at least provide an error message that the state cannot be restored. This method is called in response to an ApplicationEvent.APPEVENT_STATE_REQUEST notification. If the notification() method is overriden to process this event then this method need not be implemented. This implementation logs a warning. Do not call it from an overriding implementation.
        Parameters:
        state - An unmodifiable Map representing the state. This is a mapping of String -> String.

      • userStarted

        protected void userStarted()
        This method should be called to create the user interface objects for a "normal" invocation of the application. An application can be invoked for various reasons, such as providing features, which do not necessarily need a user interface or use a subset of the full interface. A call to this method indicates the user would like to start the application. This is called in response to an APPEVENT_USER_START_REQUEST ApplicationEvent. If the notification() method is overriden to process this event then this method need not be implemented. This implementation logs a warning. Do not call it from an overriding implementation.
